  "What are the three tenets of cell theory, and who were the key scientists who developed it?": "а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ха•З а§Єа§ња§¶а•На§Іа§Ња§Ва§§ а§Ха•З а§§а•Аа§® а§Єа§ња§¶а•На§Іа§Ња§Ва§§ а§Ха•На§ѓа§Њ а§єа•Иа§В, а§Фа§∞ а§Ха•Ма§® - а§Єа•З а§Ѓа•Ба§Ца•На§ѓ а§µа•Иа§Ьа•На§Юа§Ња§®а§ња§Х а§•а•З а§Ьа§ња§®а•На§єа•Ла§Ва§®а•З а§За§Єа•З а§µа§ња§Ха§Єа§ња§§ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ?",
  "Cell theory states: (1) all living things are made of one or more cells, (2) the cell is the basic unit of life, and (3) all new cells arise from pre-existing cells вАФ developed by Matthias Schleiden (plants, 1838), Theodor Schwann (animals, 1839), and Rudolf Virchow ('omnis cellula e cellula,' 1855), building on Robert Hooke's first observation of cells in cork (1665) and Antonie van Leeuwenhoek's observation of living cells (1670s)": "а§Ха§Ха•На§Ј а§Єа§ња§¶а•На§Іа§Ња§Ва§§ а§Ха§єа§§а§Њ а§єа•И: (а•І) а§Єа§≠а•А а§Ьа•Аа§µа§ња§§ а§Ъа•Аа§Ьа•За§В а§Па§Х а§ѓа§Њ а§Йа§Єа§Єа•З а§Еа§Іа§ња§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Єа•З а§ђа§®а•А а§єа•Иа§В, (а•®) а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ьа•Аа§µа§® а§Ха•А а§Ѓа•Ва§≤ а§За§Ха§Ња§И а§єа•И, а§Фа§∞ (а•©) а§Єа§≠а•А а§®а§И а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Єа•З а§Йа§§а•На§™а§®а•НвАНа§® а§єа•Ла§§а•А а§єа•И вАФ а§Ѓа§§а•На§§а§ња§ѓа•На§ѓа§Ња§є а§ґа•НвАНа§§а•Ла§В а§¶а•На§µа§Ња§∞а§Њ а§µа§ња§Ха§Єа§ња§§ (а§Ха§Ња§≤а•А, а•Іа•Ѓа•ѓа•ѓ), а§Фа§∞ а§µ а§µа§ња§≤а•НвАМа§Є (а§Ѓа•На§Єа§ња§≤а•А а§Ха§Њ а§Ха§Ха•На§Ј, а•Іа•Ѓа•ѓа•ѓа•Ѓ), а§∞а•Йа§ђа§∞а•На§Я а§Ха•Иа§®а§µа•НвАНа§® (а§≤а•НвАНа§®) а§Ха•З а§™а§єа§≤а•З а§Єа•За§≤ а§Ха•А а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ѓа•За§В, а§∞а•Йа§ђа§∞а•На§Я а§≤а•Аа§Уа§≤ а§Ха•А а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ха•А а§∞а§Ъа§®а§Њ (а•Іа•ђ) а§Фа§∞ а§Ьа•Аа§µ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ха•А а§ґа•Ба§∞а•Ва§Жа§§ а§Ѓа•За§Ва•§",
  "Cell theory states that only animals are made of cells, cells cannot reproduce, and cells arise spontaneously вАФ it was developed by Charles Darwin in 1859": "а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Єа§ња§¶а•На§Іа§Ња§Ва§§ а§Ха§єа§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§Єа§ња§∞а•На§Ђ а§Ьа§Ња§®а§µа§∞а•Ла§В а§Ха•Л а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Єа•З а§ђа§®а§Ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И, а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ха•Л а§¶а•Ла§ђа§Ња§∞а§Њ а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§ђа§®а§Ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Њ а§Єа§Ха§§а§Њ, а§Фа§∞ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ха•А а§∞а§Ъа§®а§Њ а§Єа§®а•НвАМ 1859 а§Ѓа•За§В а§Ъа§Ња§∞а•На§≤а•На§Є а§°а§Ња§∞а•На§µа§ња§® а§®а•З а§Ха•А а§•а•А а•§",
  "Cell theory states that cells are the smallest particles of matter, that cells are found only in plants, and that cells are created from non-living chemicals вАФ proposed by Robert Brown in 1831": "а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Єа§ња§¶а•На§Іа§Ња§Ва§§ а§Ха§єа§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ха•А а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§Єа§ђа§Єа•З а§Ыа•Ла§Яа•З а§Ха§£ а§™а§Ња§П а§Ьа§Ња§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В, а§Ха§њ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ха•Л а§™а•Ма§Іа•Ла§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а§Ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И, а§Фа§∞ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ха•Л а§Ча§Ља•Иа§∞ - а§Ьа•Аа§µа§ња§§ а§∞а§Єа§Ња§ѓа§®а•Ла§В а§Єа•З а§ђа§®а§Ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И вАФ а§Єа§®а•НвАМ 1831 а§Ѓа•За§В а§∞а•Йа§ђа§∞а•На§Я а§ђа•На§∞а§Ња§Йа§® а§¶а•На§µа§Ња§∞а§Њ а§™а•На§∞а§Єа•На§§а§Ња§µа§ња§§ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ча§ѓа§Њ",
  "Cell theory states that cells are made of atoms, that cells exist only in multicellular organisms, and that cells form from crystallization вАФ developed by Louis Pasteur": "а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ха§Њ а§Єа§ња§¶а•На§Іа§Ња§Ва§§ а§Ха§єа§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Еа§£а•Ба§Уа§В а§Єа•З а§ђа§®а•А а§єа•Ла§§а•А а§єа•И, а§Ьа•Л а§Ха§њ а§Еа§≤а§Ч - а§Еа§≤а§Ч а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а§Ња§ѓа•А а§Ьа§Ња§§а•А а§єа•Иа§В, а§Фа§∞ а§ѓа•З а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Па§Б а§Ха•На§∞а§ња§Єа•На§Яа§≤а•Аа§Ха§∞а§£ а§Єа•З а§ђа§®а•А а§єа•Ла§§а•А а§єа•Иа§В вАФ а§≤а•Ба§И а§™а§Ња§Єа•На§Ъа§∞ а§¶а•На§µа§Ња§∞а§Њ а§µа§ња§Ха§Єа§ња§§ а§Ха•А а§Ча§ѓа•А а§єа•Иа§В",
  "Cell theory вАФ foundation of modern biology: (1) Three tenets: all living things are composed of one or more cells; the cell is the fundamental unit of structure and function in living organisms; all cells arise from pre-existing cells by division. (2) Historical development: Robert Hooke (1665) coined 'cell' while examining cork under a microscope (Micrographia) вАФ saw empty cell walls. Antonie van Leeuwenhoek (1670s) вАФ first to observe living cells ('animalcules' вАФ bacteria, protists, sperm cells) using single-lens microscopes with ~270√Ч magnification. Matthias Schleiden (1838) вАФ concluded all plant tissues are composed of cells. Theodor Schwann (1839) вАФ extended to animal tissues. Rudolf Virchow (1855) вАФ 'omnis cellula e cellula' (every cell from a cell) вАФ refuted spontaneous generation of cells. (3) Modern additions: cells contain hereditary information (DNA) passed to daughter cells; all cells have the same basic chemical composition; energy flow occurs within cells. (4) Cell sizes: most 1-100 ќЉm. Smallest: Mycoplasma (~0.2 ќЉm). Largest: ostrich egg (~170 mm), Caulerpa taxifolia (single-celled alga, up to 3 m). Human cells: ~37.2 trillion.": "а§Ха§Ха•На§Ј а§Єа§ња§¶а•На§Іа§Ња§Ва§§ вАФ а§Жа§Іа•Ба§®а§ња§Х а§Ьа•Аа§µ - а§µа§ња§Ьа•На§Юа§Ња§® а§Ха•А а§ђа•Ба§®а§ња§ѓа§Ња§¶: (а•І) а§§а•Аа§® а§Ьа•Аа§µа§ња§§ а§™а§¶а§Ња§∞а•На§• а§Па§Х а§ѓа§Њ а§Йа§Єа§Єа•З а§Еа§Іа§ња§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Єа•З а§ђа§®а§Њ а§єа•Иа§В; а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ьа•Аа§µ - а§µа§ња§Ьа•На§Юа§Ња§® а§Ѓа•За§В а§Ьа§Яа§ња§≤ а§Фа§∞ а§Ха§Ња§∞а•На§ѓ а§Ха§Њ а§ђа•Ба§®а§ња§ѓа§Ња§¶а•А а§За§Ха§Ња§И а§єа•И; (а•®) а§Єа§Ња§∞а•А а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Па§Б а§Еа§≤а§Ч - а§Еа§≤а§Ч а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Єа•З а§®а§ња§Ха§≤а§§а•А а§єа•Иа§В а•§",
  "What are the key differences between prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells?": "а§Ца•Ва§® - а§Ца§∞а§Ња§ђа§Њ а§Фа§∞ а§Ца•Ва§® - а§Ца§∞а§Ња§ђа§Њ а§Ха§∞а§®а•За§µа§Ња§≤а•А а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ха•З а§ђа•Аа§Ъ а§Ха•На§ѓа§Њ а§Ђа§∞а•На§Х а§єа•И?",
  "There are no significant differences вАФ prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells have the same organelles and structures but differ only in the organisms they are found in": "а§За§Єа§Ѓа•За§В а§Ха•Ла§И а§Ѓа§єа§§а•На§§а•На§µа§™а•Ва§∞а•На§£ а§≠а§ња§®а•НвАНа§®а§§а§Њ а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§єа•И вАФ а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Ха§Яа§ња§Х а§Фа§∞ а§Па§™а•Аа§Яа§ња§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§µа§єа•А а§Еа§Ва§Ч а§Фа§∞ а§Єа§Ва§∞а§Ъа§®а§Ња§Па§Б а§™а§Ња§ѓа•А а§Ьа§Ња§§а•А а§єа•Иа§В а§≤а•За§Ха§ња§® а§Єа§ња§∞а•На§Ђа§Љ а§Ьа•Аа§µ - а§Ьа§Ва§§а•Ба§Уа§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§≠а§ња§®а•НвАНа§® а§єа•Иа§В",
  "Prokaryotic cells are larger and more complex than eukaryotic cells вАФ they have a nucleus, mitochondria, and extensive internal membranes, while eukaryotic cells lack these features": "а§За§® а§Ча•Ба§£а•Ла§В а§Ха•А а§Ха§Ѓа•А а§Єа•З а§≠а•А а§ђа§°а§Ља•З - а§ђа§°а§Ља•З а§Фа§∞ а§™а•За§Ъа•Аа§¶а§Њ а§єа•Ла§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В а•§",
  "Prokaryotic cells (bacteria and archaea) lack a membrane-bound nucleus (DNA is in a nucleoid region) and lack membrane-bound organelles вАФ they are typically smaller (0.2-5 ќЉm), have 70S ribosomes, and may have a cell wall (peptidoglycan in bacteria) вАФ eukaryotic cells (protists, fungi, plants, animals) have a true nucleus enclosed by a nuclear envelope, membrane-bound organelles (mitochondria, ER, Golgi), 80S ribosomes, and are typically larger (10-100 ќЉm)": "а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Яа§∞а•На§Ѓа§ња§ѓа§Њ (а§ђа•Иа§Ва§°а§∞а§®а§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Фа§∞ а§Ѓа§†) а§Ѓа•За§В а§Па§Х а§Іа§Ња§§а•Б а§Ха•А а§ђа§®а•А а§єа•Ба§И а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ха•А а§Ха§Ѓа•А (а§Ха§ња§Ѓа§Ња§За§° а§Ха•На§Ја•За§§а•На§∞ а§Ѓа•За§В а§єа•И) а§Фа§∞ а§Йа§Єа§Ха•А а§Ха§Ѓа•А а§≠а•А а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§єа•Ла§§а•А а§єа•И а•§",
  "Prokaryotic cells are exclusively multicellular organisms while eukaryotic cells are always single-celled вАФ this is the only distinction between the two types": "а§За§® а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§Єа§ња§∞а•На§Ђ а§Еа§≤а§Ч - а§Еа§≤а§Ч а§Ха§ња§Єа•На§Ѓ а§Ха•З а§Ьа•Аа§µ а§єа•Ла§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В, а§Ьа§ђа§Ха§њ а§ѓа•З а§єа§Ѓа•За§ґа§Њ а§Па§Х - а§¶а•Ва§Єа§∞а•З а§Єа•З а§Ьа•Ба§°а§Ља•З а§єа•Ла§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В вАФ а§ѓа•З а§¶а•Л а§Ха§ња§Єа•На§Ѓ а§Ха•З а§ђа•Аа§Ъ а§Ха§Њ а§Ђа§∞а•На§Х а§єа•И",
  "Prokaryotic vs. eukaryotic cells: (1) Prokaryotes ('before nucleus'): Domains Bacteria and Archaea. No nuclear envelope вАФ circular DNA in nucleoid region (+ plasmids). No membrane-bound organelles. Small: 0.2-5 ќЉm typically. 70S ribosomes (50S + 30S subunits). Cell wall: peptidoglycan in bacteria (Gram + thick, Gram вИТ thin + outer membrane); pseudopeptidoglycan or S-layer in archaea. Reproduce by binary fission. (2) Eukaryotes ('true nucleus'): Domain Eukarya вАФ protists, fungi, plants, animals. True nucleus with double membrane (nuclear envelope with nuclear pores). Membrane-bound organelles: mitochondria, ER, Golgi, lysosomes, (chloroplasts in plants/algae). Larger: 10-100 ќЉm typically. 80S ribosomes (60S + 40S). Linear chromosomes with histones. Reproduce by mitosis/meiosis. (3) Endosymbiotic theory (Lynn Margulis, 1967): mitochondria and chloroplasts were once free-living prokaryotes engulfed by ancestral eukaryotic cells вАФ evidence: double membranes, own circular DNA, 70S ribosomes, binary fission-like division, size similar to bacteria.": "а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Ха•На§ґа§® а§µа•А. (а§µа§ња§Єа•На§Ха§Ња§∞ а§Ха•З а§™а§єа§≤а•З) а§Иа§∞а§Ња§За§Са§Єа•На§Єа•НвАМ (а§Єа•На§Ха§Ња§∞а§Х); а§°а•Ла§Ѓа•За§® а§ђа•Иа§Ха•На§ђа•Йа§Яа§∞ а§§а§•а§Њ а§Жа§∞а•На§Ъа•А а§Ьа•Иа§Єа•З а§Еа§£а•Ба§Уа§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§≠а•А а§™а§Ња§П а§Ьа§Ња§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В. а§Па§®. а§Па§®. а§Па§®. а§Па§Є. а§Па§Є. а§Па§Є.",
  "What is the structure of the cell membrane according to the fluid mosaic model?": "а§™а§Ња§®а•А а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а§Ња§ѓа•А а§Ьа§Ња§®а•За§µа§Ња§≤а•А а§∞а•За§ґа§Ѓ а§Ха•А а§ђа§®а§Ња§µа§Я а§Ха•З а§Ѓа•Ба§§а§Ња§ђа§ња§Х, а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а§Ња§П а§Ьа§Ња§®а•За§µа§Ња§≤а•З а§™а§Ња§П а§Ьа§Ња§®а•За§µа§Ња§≤а•З а§Еа§£а•Ба§Уа§В а§Ха•А а§ђа§®а§Ња§µа§Я а§Ха•На§ѓа§Њ а§єа•И?",
  "The cell membrane is a single layer of carbohydrate molecules with no lipids or proteins, functioning only as a physical shield against mechanical damage": "а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а§Ња§П а§Ьа§Ња§®а•За§µа§Ња§≤а•З а§Еа§£а•Ба§Уа§В а§Ха•А а§Па§Х а§™а§∞а§§ а§єа•Ла§§а•А а§єа•И, а§Ьа§ња§Єа§Ѓа•За§В а§® а§§а•Л а§єа•Ла§Ва§† а§ѓа§Њ а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Яа•Аа§® а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§єа•Ла§§а•З а§Фа§∞ а§® а§єа•А а§Йа§®а•На§єа•За§В а§Па§Х а§єа•А а§Ъа•Аа§Ьа§Љ а§Ха•З а§§а•Ма§∞ а§™а§∞ а§Ха§Ња§Ѓ а§Ха§∞а§®а•З а§Ха•З а§≤а§ња§П а§За§Єа•На§§а•За§Ѓа§Ња§≤ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И а•§",
  "The cell membrane is composed entirely of DNA wrapped around histone proteins, serving both as a boundary and as the cell's genetic material storage site": "а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а§Ња§П а§Ьа§Ња§®а•За§µа§Ња§≤а•З DNA а§Ха•А а§™а•Ва§∞а•А а§§а§∞а§є а§Єа•З а§∞а§Ъа§®а§Њ а§єа•Ла§§а•А а§єа•И а§Ьа§ња§Єа§Ѓа•За§В а§Па§Х а§єа•А а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Яа•Аа§® а§єа•Ла§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В, а§¶а•Ла§®а•Ла§В а§Па§Х а§Єа•Аа§Ѓа§Њ а§Ха•З а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Ѓа•За§В а§Єа•За§µа§Њ а§Ха§∞а§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В а§Фа§∞ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ха•З а§Жа§®а•Ба§µа§Ва§ґа§ња§Х а§™а§¶а§Ња§∞а•На§• а§≠а§Ва§°а§Ња§∞а§£ а§Єа•На§•а§≤ а§Ха•З а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Ѓа•За§В",
  "According to the fluid mosaic model (Singer & Nicolson, 1972), the cell membrane is a phospholipid bilayer with hydrophilic heads facing outward and hydrophobic tails facing inward вАФ proteins are embedded in or attached to this bilayer (integral/transmembrane proteins and peripheral proteins), along with cholesterol (in animal cells, regulates fluidity), glycoproteins, and glycolipids вАФ the membrane is 'fluid' because components can move laterally": "а§¶а•На§∞а§µ а§∞а§Єа§Ња§ѓа§® а§Ѓа•Йа§°а§≤ а§Ха•З а§Еа§®а•Ба§Єа§Ња§∞ (а§Єа§ња§Ва§Ча§∞ а§Фа§∞ а§®а•Аа§Єа•На§Яа§ња§®а§Єа§®, 1972) а§Єа•За§≤ а§™а•На§≤а•За§Я, а§ђа§Ња§єа§∞а•А а§Фа§∞ а§≤а§Ња§≤ а§∞а§Ха•НвАНа§§ - а§µа§Ња§єа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ха§Њ а§Єа§Ња§Ѓа§®а§Њ а§Ха§∞а§§а•А а§єа•И а•§",
  "The cell membrane is a rigid, solid wall of pure protein that forms an impermeable barrier around the cell, preventing all substances from entering or leaving": "а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а§Ња§П а§Ьа§Ња§®а•За§µа§Ња§≤а•З а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Яа•Аа§® а§Ха§Њ а§Па§Х а§Єа§Ца•На§§ а§Фа§∞ а§†а•Ла§Є а§¶а•Аа§µа§Ња§∞ а§єа•И, а§Ьа•Л а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ха•З а§Ъа§Ња§∞а•Ла§В а§Уа§∞ а§Па§Х а§Еа§Яа•Ва§Я а§ђа§Ња§Іа§Њ а§ђа§®а§Ња§§а•А а§єа•И, а§Ьа§ња§Єа§Ѓа•За§В а§Єа§≠а•А а§™а§¶а§Ња§∞а•На§• а§™а•На§∞а§µа•За§ґ а§Ха§∞а§®а•З а§ѓа§Њ а§Ыа•Ла§°а§Ља§®а•З а§Єа•З а§∞а•Ла§Х а§¶а§ња§П а§Ьа§Ња§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В",
  "Cell membrane вАФ fluid mosaic model: (1) Phospholipid bilayer: each phospholipid has a hydrophilic head (phosphate group + glycerol) and two hydrophobic fatty acid tails вЖТ spontaneously forms bilayer in aqueous environment. ~5 nm thick. (2) 'Fluid': lipids and proteins move laterally within the bilayer (lateral diffusion: ~2 ќЉm/sec for lipids). Flip-flop (transverse movement) is rare without flippase enzymes. (3) 'Mosaic': diverse proteins scattered through the membrane. Integral/transmembrane proteins: span entire bilayer (channels, carriers, receptors). Peripheral proteins: attached to surface (enzymes, cytoskeletal anchors). (4) Cholesterol: ~20% of animal cell membrane lipids. Wedges between phospholipids вАФ at high temperature reduces fluidity (restricts movement); at low temperature prevents solidification (disrupts packing). Absent in most prokaryotes. (5) Glycocalyx: carbohydrate chains on glycoproteins and glycolipids (extracellular surface) вАФ cell recognition, protection, cell-cell adhesion. Blood type antigens (A, B, O) are glycolipids/glycoproteins. (6) Selective permeability: small nonpolar molecules (OвВВ, COвВВ, NвВВ) pass freely; small polar molecules (HвВВO, ethanol) pass slowly; ions and large molecules require transport proteins.": "а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ха•А а§ђа§®а§Ња§µа§Я вАФ а§™а§Ња§®а•А а§Ха•А а§ђа§®а§Ња§µа§Я: (а•І) а§≤а•За§Ђа•Йа§Ђа•Йа§За§° а§•а•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§За§Єа§∞а§Ња§За§°а§∞: а§єа§∞ а§Ѓа•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§ѓа§∞ а§Ха§Њ а§Єа§ња§∞ (а§Єа•На§Ђа•Аа§≤а§Њ) а§єа•Ла§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Фа§∞ а§¶а•Л а§ђа•На§≤а§Ња§За§°а§Ња§За§° а§Еа§Ѓа•На§≤а•А а§Еа§Ѓа•На§≤а•А а§єа•Ба§И а§єа•И а•§ (а•®)",
  "What is the structure and function of the nucleus in eukaryotic cells?": "а§Па§Са§Ха§Ња§За§Яа•НвАМа§∞а•А а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§Ха•За§Ва§¶а•На§∞ а§Ха§Њ а§Єа§Ва§∞а§Ъа§®а§Њ а§Фа§∞ а§Ха§Ња§∞а•На§ѓ а§Ха•На§ѓа§Њ а§єа•И?",
  "The nucleus is found only in plant cells and functions exclusively to store starch granules and pigment molecules used in photosynthesis": "а§™а•На§∞а§Ха§Ња§ґ - а§Єа§Ва§ґа•НвАНа§≤а•За§Ја§£ а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а•На§∞а§ѓа•Ла§Ч а§Ха§ња§П а§Ьа§Ња§®а•За§µа§Ња§≤а•З а§§а§Ња§∞а•Ла§В а§Фа§∞ а§Єа§Ва§µа§∞а•На§Іа§® а§Еа§£а•Ба§Уа§В а§Ха•Л а§Ьа§Ѓа§Њ а§Ха§∞а§®а•З а§Ха•З а§≤а§ња§П а§Ха•За§Ва§¶а•На§∞ а§Ха•За§µа§≤ а§™а•Ма§Іа•Ла§В а§Ха•А а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Фа§∞ а§Ха§Ња§∞а•На§ѓа•Ла§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а§Ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И",
  "The nucleus is the site of ATP production through oxidative phosphorylation вАФ it contains cristae and an electron transport chain identical to mitochondria": "а§Ѓа§Іа•На§ѓ а§ѓа•Ба§Ч а§Ха§Њ а§Ѓа§Іа•На§ѓ - а§Ха•За§Ва§¶а•На§∞ а§єа•И, а§єа§Ња§•а•А - а§¶а§Ња§Ба§§ а§Ха•З а§Ьа§Ља§∞а§ња§П а§ђа§®а§Ња§П а§Ча§П а§Йа§§а•На§™а§Ња§¶а§® а§Ха•А а§Ьа§Ча§є а•§",
  "The nucleus is surrounded by a double membrane (nuclear envelope) with nuclear pores that regulate transport вАФ it contains the cell's DNA organized into chromatin (dispersed during interphase) or chromosomes (condensed during division), a nucleolus (site of ribosomal RNA synthesis and ribosome assembly), and serves as the control center directing gene expression, DNA replication, and cell division": "а§Ѓа§Іа•На§ѓ а§Ха•За§Ва§¶а•На§∞ а§Ѓа•За§В а§Па§Х а§°а§ђа§≤ а§Іа§Ња§§а•Б (nuulhing) а§Єа•З а§Ша§ња§∞а§Њ а§єа•Ба§Ж а§єа•И а§Ьа•Л а§™а§∞а§ња§µа§єа§® а§Ха•Л а§®а§ња§ѓа§Ва§§а•На§∞а§ња§§ а§Ха§∞а§§а§Њ а§єа•И вАФ а§ѓа§є а§Ха§Ха•На§Ј а§Ха•З а§°а•Аа§У а§Ха•З а§°а•А. а§Па§®. а§Па§®. а§П.",
  "The nucleus is a small, membrane-free region that contains only RNA вАФ it functions exclusively to produce lipids for the cell membrane and has no role in genetic information": "а§Ѓа§Іа•На§ѓ а§Ха•За§Ва§¶а•На§∞ а§Па§Х а§Ыа•Ла§Яа§Њ, а§Ча•Ла§≤ а§Ха•На§Ја•За§§а•На§∞ а§єа•И а§Ьа§ња§Єа§Ѓа•За§В а§Ха•За§µа§≤ RNA а§ґа§Ња§Ѓа§ња§≤ а§єа•И вАФ а§ѓа§є а§Єа§ња§∞а•На§Ђ а§Ха§Ха•На§Ј а§Ха•А а§®а§≤а•А а§Ха•З а§≤а§ња§П а§єа•Ла§Ва§† а§™а•Иа§¶а§Њ а§Ха§∞а§®а•З а§Ха•З а§≤а§ња§П а§Ха§Ња§∞а•На§ѓ а§Ха§∞а§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Фа§∞ а§Жа§®а•Ба§µа§Ва§ґа§ња§Х а§Ьа§Ња§®а§Ха§Ња§∞а•А а§Ѓа•За§В а§Ха•Ла§И а§≠а•Ва§Ѓа§ња§Ха§Њ а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§єа•И",
  "The nucleus вАФ command center of the cell: (1) Nuclear envelope: double membrane (outer continuous with rough ER). Nuclear pores (~3,000-4,000 per nucleus): large protein complexes (nucleoporins, ~120 MDa) that regulate bidirectional transport вАФ small molecules diffuse freely; large molecules (proteins, RNA) require nuclear localization signals (NLS) and importin/exportin proteins (Ran-GTP cycle). (2) Chromatin: DNA + histone proteins. Euchromatin (loosely packed, transcriptionally active) vs. heterochromatin (tightly packed, mostly inactive). During cell division: chromatin condenses into visible chromosomes. Humans: 46 chromosomes (23 pairs). (3) Nucleolus: dense region within nucleus (not membrane-bound). Site of rRNA transcription (by RNA Pol I) and ribosome subunit assembly. rRNA genes are clustered on chromosomes 13, 14, 15, 21, 22 in humans (nucleolar organizer regions). Can have 1-4 nucleoli per nucleus. (4) Nuclear lamina: meshwork of intermediate filaments (lamins A, B, C) lining inner nuclear membrane вАФ provides structural support, anchors chromatin, involved in DNA replication. Mutations in lamin A вЖТ progeria (Hutchinson-Gilford syndrome: premature aging). (5) Functions: DNA storage/protection, transcription (DNA вЖТ mRNA), RNA processing (splicing, capping, polyadenylation), ribosome assembly, cell cycle regulation.": "а§Ѓа•За§∞а§≤ вАФ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ха§Њ а§®а§ња§∞а•На§¶а•За§ґ а§Ха•За§Ва§¶а•На§∞: (а•І) а§Ѓа§Ња§За§Ха•На§∞а•Ла§Єа•На§Ха•Ла§™а§Ха•На§ґа§® (а§Єа§Ва§Ха§Ња§∞а§Х) а§°а§ђа§≤ а§Іа§Ња§§а•Б (а§ђа§Ња§єа§∞ а§Єа•З а§Ьа§Ња§∞а•А а§єа•И)а•§ а§Іа§Ња§§а•Б а§Ха•З а§ђа§°а§Ља•З а§Ьа§Яа§ња§≤, а§Єа•Ла§®а•З а§Ха•А а§µа•На§ѓа§µа§Єа•На§•а§Ња§Па§Б (а§Па§®.а§Па§Є. а§Па§®. а§µа•А. а§µа•А. а§µа•А.)",
  "How do mitochondria produce ATP, and what evidence supports the endosymbiotic theory of their origin?": "а§Па§Ѓа•На§ђа•На§∞а§ња§ѓа§Њ а§®а•З а§Па§Яа•Аа§™а•А а§Ха•А а§∞а§Ъа§®а§Њ а§Ха•Иа§Єа•З а§Ха•А, а§Фа§∞ а§Ха•Ма§® - а§Єа§Њ а§™а•На§∞а§Ѓа§Ња§£ а§Йа§®а§Ха•З а§Йа§¶а•НвАМа§Ча§Ѓ а§Ха•З а§Еа§Ва§§а•Аа§ѓ а§Єа§ња§¶а•На§Іа§Ња§Ва§§ а§Ха§Њ а§Єа§Ѓа§∞а•На§•а§® а§Ха§∞а§§а§Њ а§єа•И?",
  "Mitochondria do not produce ATP вАФ they function only as storage vesicles for calcium ions and were formed by invagination of the cell membrane during evolution, driven by the interacting mechanisms of mutation, genetic drift, gene flow, and natural selection operating across many generations": "",
  "Mitochondria produce ATP by photosynthesis using chlorophyll pigments вАФ they originated from plant cells that were incorporated into animal cells through grafting, which has been well-documented through controlled experimental studies and long-term ecological monitoring programs across many regions": "",
  "Mitochondria produce ATP by breaking down DNA into nucleotides вАФ they have always been part of eukaryotic cells and share no evolutionary relationship with bacteria, involving comprehensive analysis of genomic markers and heritable phenotypic variation within and between natural populations": "",
  "Mitochondria produce ATP through cellular respiration: pyruvate from glycolysis enters the matrix for the citric acid cycle, then electrons pass through the electron transport chain, creating a proton gradient that drives ATP synthase (chemiosmosis) вАФ producing ~30-32 ATP per glucose вАФ endosymbiotic evidence includes their own circular DNA, 70S ribosomes, double membrane, binary fission-like division, and size similar to bacteria": "",
  "Mitochondria вАФ powerhouse of the cell: (1) Structure: double membrane вАФ outer membrane (permeable via porins), inner membrane (highly folded into cristae вАФ greatly increases surface area for ATP production), intermembrane space, matrix (contains enzymes, circular DNA, 70S ribosomes). (2) ATP production pathway: glycolysis (cytoplasm): glucose вЖТ 2 pyruvate + 2 ATP + 2 NADH. Pyruvate enters mitochondrial matrix вЖТ pyruvate dehydrogenase вЖТ acetyl-CoA + COвВВ + NADH. Citric acid (Krebs) cycle: acetyl-CoA вЖТ 2 COвВВ + 3 NADH + 1 FADHвВВ + 1 GTP per turn (√Ч2 per glucose). Electron transport chain (inner membrane): NADH вЖТ Complex I вЖТ ubiquinone вЖТ Complex III вЖТ cytochrome c вЖТ Complex IV вЖТ OвВВ + HвВВO. FADHвВВ вЖТ Complex II вЖТ ubiquinone. Protons pumped to intermembrane space вЖТ proton-motive force. ATP synthase (Complex V): HвБЇ flow back through rotary motor вЖТ ADP + Pi вЖТ ATP. (3) Yield: ~30-32 ATP per glucose (variable). (4) Endosymbiotic theory (Lynn Margulis, 1967): ancestral eukaryote engulfed aerobic ќ±-proteobacterium вЖТ mutualistic endosymbiosis. Evidence: own circular DNA (~16,569 bp in humans, encoding 37 genes); 70S ribosomes (bacterial type); double membrane (inner = original bacterial membrane); divide by binary fission independently of cell cycle; size/shape similar to bacteria (~1-10 ќЉm); phylogenetic analysis shows mitochondrial genes are closest to Rickettsiales (ќ±-proteobacteria). (5) Maternal inheritance: mitochondrial DNA inherited exclusively from mother (egg contributes ~100,000 mitochondria; sperm mitochondria are destroyed after fertilization).": "",
  "What are ribosomes, and how do free and bound ribosomes differ in function?": "а§¶а§Ња§Ба§§а•Ла§В а§Ха§Њ а§ђа§Ња§єа§∞а•А а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Ха•На§ѓа§Њ а§єа•И, а§Фа§∞ а§Ха•Иа§Єа•З а§Ѓа•Ба§Ха•НвАНа§§ а§Фа§∞ а§ђа§Ња§Іа•На§ѓа§Ха§Ња§∞а•А а§Ха§Ња§Ѓ а§Ѓа•За§В а§≠а§ња§®а•НвАНа§® а§єа•Иа§В?",
  "Ribosomes are DNA-replicating structures found only in the nucleus вАФ there is no difference between free and bound ribosomes as they both replicate DNA at the same rate": "Robobooss а§Ха•За§µа§≤ а§Ѓа§Іа•На§ѓ а§Ха•За§Ва§¶а•На§∞ а§Ѓа•За§В а§Ѓа§ња§≤а•З DNA-round а§Єа§Ва§∞а§Ъа§®а§Ња§Па§Б а§єа•Иа§В - а§Ѓа•Ба§Ха•На§§ а§Фа§∞ а§ђа§Ња§Іа•На§ѓа§Ха§Ња§∞а•А а§Еа§£а•На§°а•Ла§В а§Ха•З а§ђа•Аа§Ъ а§Ха•Ла§И а§Ђа§∞а•На§Х а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§єа•И а§Ха•На§ѓа•Ла§Ва§Ха§њ а§µа•З а§¶а•Ла§®а•Ла§В а§Па§Х а§єа•А а§¶а§∞ а§™а§∞ а§Па§Х а§єа•А а§§а§∞а§є а§Єа•З а§Па§® а§Ђа§ња§∞ а§Єа•З а§Ча•Ба§£а§Њ а§Ха§∞а§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В",
  "Ribosomes are membrane-bound organelles that produce lipids вАФ free ribosomes make phospholipids while bound ribosomes make cholesterol, and they are found only in eukaryotic cells": "Roboboboocssssssclocssssshrocsssshops а§Ьа§ђ scipsssss, а§Фа§∞ а§µа•З а§Ха•За§µа§≤ lacopiocs а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а§Ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И",
  "Ribosomes are complexes of rRNA and protein that synthesize proteins by translating mRNA вАФ free ribosomes (in cytoplasm) produce proteins used within the cell (cytoplasmic enzymes, cytoskeletal proteins), while bound ribosomes (attached to rough ER) produce proteins destined for secretion, membrane insertion, or organelle targeting вАФ eukaryotic ribosomes are 80S (60S + 40S) while prokaryotic are 70S (50S + 30S)": "RRNA а§Фа§∞ а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Яа•Аа§® а§Ха•З а§Ьа§Яа§ња§≤ а§єа•Ла§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В а§Ьа•Л mRNA а§Ха§Њ а§Еа§®а•Ба§µа§Ња§¶ а§Ха§∞а§®а•З а§Ха•З а§¶а•На§µа§Ња§∞а§Њ а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Яа•Аа§® а§Йа§§а•На§™а§®а•НвАНа§® а§Ха§∞а§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В вАФ а§Єа•На§µа§§а§Ва§§а•На§∞ а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Єа•З а§™а§¶а§Ња§∞а•На§• (а§Єа§Ва§§а•На§∞а§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ѓа•За§В) а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ха•З а§Еа§®а•На§¶а§∞ а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Яа•Аа§® а§Йа§§а•На§™а§®а•НвАНа§® а§Ха§∞а§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В (а§Єа§Ва§§а•На§∞а•НвАНа§® а§єа•Ла§§а§Њ а§єа•И), а§Ьа§ђа§Ха§њ а§Ча•Ба§™а•На§§ а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Яа•Аа§® а§Ха•Л а§Йа§§а•На§™а§®а•НвАНа§® а§Ха§∞а§®а•З а§Ха•З а§≤а§ња§П а§За§Єа•На§§а•За§Ѓа§Ња§≤ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И, а§Ьа§ња§Єа•З а§Ча•Ба§™а•На§§ а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Яа•Аа§® а§ѓа§Њ а§Ча•Ба§™а•На§§ а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Єа•З а§Йа§§а•На§™а§®а•НвАНа§® а§Ха§∞а§®а•З а§Ха•З а§≤а§ња§П а§За§Єа•На§§а•За§Ѓа§Ња§≤ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И, а§Фа§∞ а§Ьа§ња§Єа•З а§Ча•Ба§™а•На§§ а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Яа•Аа§® (а§Єа§Ва§Єа•НвАНа§® а§Ха§∞а§®а•З а§Ха•З а§≤а§ња§П а§Еа§≠а•На§ѓа•На§ѓа•На§ѓа•На§ѓа•На§ѓа•На§ѓа•На§ѓа•На§ѓа•На§ѓа•На§ѓа•На§ѓа•На§ѓа•На§ѓа•На§ѓа§® а§Ха§∞ а§∞а§єа•З а§єа•Иа§В) (S) (SSSSSS) (SSSS) (S) (SERS)",
  "Ribosomes are storage granules that accumulate starch and glycogen вАФ free ribosomes store starch while bound ribosomes store glycogen in specialized vacuoles": "а§∞а•Аа§ђа•Ла§Є а§Ра§Єа•З а§≠а§Ва§°а§Ња§∞ а§єа•Ла§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В а§Ьа•Л а§§а§Ња§∞а•Ла§В а§Фа§∞ gocates а§За§Ха§Яа•На§†а§Њ а§Ха§∞а§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В вАФ а§Ца§Ња§≤а•А а§Ѓа§ња§Яа•На§Яа•А а§Ѓа•За§В а§§а§Ња§∞а•Ла§В а§Ха§Њ а§≠а§Ва§°а§Ња§∞ а§ђа§®а§Ња§§а•З а§Єа§Ѓа§ѓ а§Ьа§ђа§Ха§њ а§µа§ња§ґа§ња§Ја•На§Я sclocrams а§Ѓа•За§В loclocons а§Ьа§Ѓа§Њ а§Ха§∞а§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В",
  "Ribosomes вАФ protein synthesis machinery: (1) Structure: not membrane-bound organelles вАФ composed of ribosomal RNA (rRNA) + proteins. Two subunits: large + small. Eukaryotic: 80S total (60S large + 40S small; 'S' = Svedberg unit, sedimentation rate вАФ not additive). Prokaryotic: 70S (50S + 30S). (2) Function: translate mRNA into polypeptide chains. mRNA binds to small subunit вЖТ initiator tRNA (Met-tRNA) binds to start codon (AUG) вЖТ large subunit joins вЖТ elongation: aminoacyl-tRNAs enter A site, peptide bond forms (peptidyl transferase вАФ actually a ribozyme, catalyzed by rRNA), translocation to P site вЖТ termination at stop codon (UAA, UAG, UGA). (3) Free ribosomes: float in cytoplasm. Produce proteins for intracellular use вАФ cytoplasmic enzymes (glycolytic enzymes), cytoskeletal proteins (actin, tubulin), peripheral membrane proteins. (4) Bound ribosomes: attached to rough ER membrane. Produce proteins with signal peptides (N-terminal hydrophobic sequence recognized by signal recognition particle/SRP) вЖТ protein threaded into ER lumen вЖТ folding, glycosylation вЖТ vesicle transport to Golgi. Products: secreted proteins (hormones, antibodies), membrane proteins (receptors, channels), lysosomal enzymes. (5) Same ribosomes can be free or bound вАФ determined by the mRNA being translated (presence/absence of signal peptide sequence). (6) Clinical significance: prokaryotic vs. eukaryotic ribosome differences are exploited by antibiotics вАФ tetracycline (blocks tRNA binding to 30S), chloramphenicol (inhibits peptidyl transferase on 50S), erythromycin (blocks translocation on 50S). These don't affect human 80S ribosomes вЖТ selective toxicity.": "",
  "What are the structural and functional differences between rough ER and smooth ER?": "",
  "Rough ER and smooth ER are identical in structure and function вАФ the 'rough' designation simply refers to ER that has been damaged during cell aging": "",
  "Rough ER produces ATP while smooth ER produces DNA вАФ they are separate, unconnected organelles found in different cell types": "",
  "Rough ER has ribosomes on its surface and is involved in protein synthesis, folding, and modification вАФ smooth ER lacks ribosomes and is involved in lipid synthesis, calcium storage, and detoxification вАФ both are continuous membrane systems connected to the nuclear envelope": "",
  "Rough ER is found only in plant cells and smooth ER is found only in animal cells вАФ neither is involved in protein or lipid synthesis": "а§® а§Єа§ња§∞а•На§Ђ а§™а•Ма§Іа•Ла§В а§Ха•А а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§ђа§≤а•На§Ха§њ а§Ъа§ња§Ха§®а•А - а§Ъа•Ба§™а§°а§Ља•А а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§≠а•А а§™а§Ња§ѓа•А а§Ьа§Ња§§а•А а§єа•И а•§",
  "Endoplasmic reticulum (ER): (1) Rough ER (RER): studded with ribosomes on cytoplasmic surface. Functions: protein synthesis (secretory, membrane, lysosomal proteins translated on bound ribosomes), protein folding (chaperones: BiP/GRP78, calnexin), quality control (misfolded proteins вЖТ ERAD: ER-associated degradation вЖТ proteasome), N-linked glycosylation (oligosaccharide transferred to Asn residues by oligosaccharyltransferase), disulfide bond formation (protein disulfide isomerase/PDI). Prominent in cells that secrete proteins: plasma cells (antibodies), pancreatic acinar cells (digestive enzymes), goblet cells (mucus). (2) Smooth ER (SER): no ribosomes. Functions: lipid/phospholipid synthesis (phosphatidylcholine, sphingomyelin), steroid hormone synthesis (in adrenal cortex, gonads вАФ SER abundant), detoxification (cytochrome P450 enzymes in liver вАФ oxidize drugs, toxins, ethanol вАФ chronic alcohol вЖТ SER proliferation), carbohydrate metabolism (glucose-6-phosphatase in liver converts G6P вЖТ glucose for export), calcium storage/release (sarcoplasmic reticulum in muscle вАФ specialized SER that releases Ca¬≤вБЇ for contraction). (3) ER stress: accumulation of misfolded proteins вЖТ unfolded protein response (UPR) вЖТ if unresolved вЖТ apoptosis. Relevant in: diabetes (ќ≤-cells), neurodegenerative diseases (Alzheimer's, Parkinson's).": "а§Ѓа•Ба§Ца•На§ѓ а§Еа§Іа•На§ѓа§ѓа§® а§Єа•З а§™а§§а§Њ а§Ъа§≤а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§∞а§Ха•НвАНа§§ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Па§Б (а§µа§ња§∞а•Ла§Іа§њ), а§∞а§Ха•НвАНа§§ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Па§Б (а§Єа§Ва§§а•На§∞), а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•Ба§≤а•НвАМа§Є, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМа§Є, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМа§Є, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМа§Є (а§Єа•НвАМ), а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМ, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМа§Єа•НвАМ, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМ (а§Єа•НвАМ), а§∞а§Ха•НвАНа§§а•НвАНа§§, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАНа§§, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМа§Є, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМа§Єа•НвАМ, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМ, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМа§Є, а§ѓа§Њ а§≤а•Ла§≤а§Њ), а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМа§Є (а§Є), а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМа§Єа•НвАМ, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМ, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМа§Єа•НвАМа§Є), а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМ, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•НвАМа§Є (а§Є).",
  "What is the function of the Golgi apparatus, and how does it process and sort proteins?": "а§Фа§∞ а§ѓа§є а§Ха§ња§Є а§§а§∞а§є а§Ха§Ња§Ѓ а§Ха§∞а§§а•А а§єа•И а§Фа§∞ а§Ха§ња§Є а§§а§∞а§є а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Яа•Аа§® а§Ха§∞а§§а§Њ а§єа•И?",
  "The Golgi apparatus (discovered by Camillo Golgi, 1898) receives proteins from the ER in transport vesicles, then modifies them (glycosylation, phosphorylation, sulfation), sorts them by adding molecular 'address tags' (e.g., mannose-6-phosphate tag directs proteins to lysosomes), and packages them into vesicles for delivery to their final destinations вАФ the plasma membrane, lysosomes, or secretion outside the cell": "GLLLANTACAL а§Йа§™а§Ха§∞а§£ (CALALLLLLLALLLLLLLLLLLG, 1898) а§Ха•З а§¶а•На§µа§Ња§∞а§Њ а§™а•На§∞а§Ња§™а•На§§ а§єа•Ла§§а§Њ а§єа•И, а§Ђа§ња§∞ а§За§®а•На§єа•За§В ssssssssss (grocization), sclocrips, Grops, а§Фа§∞ shripty's (gs) а§Ха•З а§Яа•Иа§Ч а§Ьа•Ла§°а§Ља§®а•З а§Ха•З а§¶а•На§µа§Ња§∞а§Њ а§µа•З а§Еа§™а§®а•З а§Еа§Ва§§а§ња§Ѓ а§™а•Иа§Ха•За§Ьа•Ла§В а§Ха•Л а§µа•На§ѓа§µа§Єа•На§•а§ња§§ а§Ха§∞а§§а§Њ а§єа•И, а§Фа§∞ а§Йа§®а§Ха•З а§ђа§Ња§єа§∞а•А а§ђа§Ња§єа§∞а•А а§Ча§Ва§§а§µа•На§ѓ а§Ха•З а§≤а§ња§П а§Ча•Ба§™а•На§§ а§™а•Иа§Ха•За§Ьа•Ла§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§ґа§Ња§Ѓа§ња§≤ а§Ха§∞а§§а§Њ а§єа•И.",
  "The Golgi apparatus is a temporary structure that forms only during cell division to separate chromosomes вАФ it disassembles after mitosis is complete": "а§Ча•Ла§≤а§ња§Ьа•А а§Йа§™а§Ха§∞а§£ а§Па§Х а§Еа§Єа•На§•а§Ња§ѓа•А а§Єа§Ва§∞а§Ъа§®а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ьа•Л а§Ха•За§µа§≤ а§Ха§Ха•На§Ј а§µа§ња§≠а§Ња§Ьа§® а§Ха•З а§¶а•Ма§∞а§Ња§® а§єа•А а§Ђа§Ња§∞а•На§Ѓа•Ла§В а§Ха•Л а§Еа§≤а§Ч а§Ха§∞а§®а•З а§Ха•З а§≤а§ња§П а§Ха§∞а§§а•А а§єа•И вАФ а§ѓа§є а§Ѓа§ња§Єа§ња§Є а§Ха•З а§™а•Ва§∞а•З а§єа•Ла§®а•З а§Ха•З а§ђа§Ња§¶ а§≠а§Ва§Ч а§єа•Ла§§а§Њ а§єа•И",
  "The Golgi apparatus stores DNA and produces ribosomes вАФ it is identical in function to the nucleolus and is found only in prokaryotic cells": "а§Ча•Ла§≤а§ња§µа•А а§Йа§™а§Ха§∞а§£ а§П. а§°а•А. а§°а•А.",
  "The Golgi apparatus is the cell's energy-producing organelle that generates ATP by oxidizing fatty acids вАФ it has no role in protein modification or sorting": "GLAL MLAN а§Йа§™а§Ха§∞а§£ а§єа•И а§Єа•За§≤ а§Ка§∞а•На§Ьа§Њ-procents а§єа•И а§Ьа•Л а§Па§Х а§Жа§Иа§Яа•Аа§™а•А а§Еа§Ѓа•На§≤ а§ђа§®а§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И - а§ѓа§є а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Яа•Аа§® а§™а§∞а§ња§µа§∞а•На§Іа§® а§ѓа§Њ а§Ыа§Ва§Яа§Ња§И а§Ѓа•За§В а§Ха•Ла§И а§≠а•Ва§Ѓа§ња§Ха§Њ а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§єа•И",
  "Golgi apparatus вАФ the cell's processing and shipping center: (1) Structure: stack of flattened membrane-bound sacs (cisternae), typically 4-8 per stack. Polarized: cis face (receiving side, near ER) вЖТ medial cisternae вЖТ trans face (shipping side, near plasma membrane). Trans-Golgi network (TGN): sorting station. (2) Receiving: COPII-coated vesicles bud from ER вЖТ fuse with cis-Golgi. (3) Modification: further glycosylation (N-linked oligosaccharides trimmed and modified; O-linked glycosylation added); phosphorylation; sulfation; proteolytic cleavage (e.g., proinsulin вЖТ insulin + C-peptide). (4) Sorting: mannose-6-phosphate (M6P) tag вЖТ M6P receptor вЖТ lysosomal delivery. Signal sequences on proteins determine routing. (5) Packaging and export: constitutive secretion (default pathway вАФ continuous vesicle fusion with plasma membrane), regulated secretion (vesicles stored, released on signal вАФ e.g., neurotransmitters, hormones), retrograde transport (COPI vesicles: Golgi вЖТ ER, retrieves escaped ER-resident proteins with KDEL signal). (6) Camillo Golgi discovered the apparatus in 1898 using silver nitrate staining of Purkinje neurons вАФ shared Nobel Prize 1906 with Santiago Ram√≥n y Cajal. (7) Clinical: I-cell disease (mucolipidosis II) вАФ deficiency of GlcNAc phosphotransferase вЖТ proteins lack M6P tag вЖТ lysosomal enzymes secreted instead of delivered to lysosomes вЖТ cellular waste accumulates.": "а§На§∞а•Ла§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§За§Є (а§Еа§Ва§Ча•На§∞а•За§Ьа§Ља•А); \"а§≤а§ња§Ђа§Ља§ња§Ђа§Ља•Йа§За§Є\" (а§Еа§Ва§Ча•На§∞а•За§Ьа§Ља•А) а§Ха•З а§ђа§Ьа§Ња§ѓ, а§•а•Йа§∞а•На§®а§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ха•З а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а§∞ (а§µа§ња§Єа•На§Єа•На§≤а§Њ) (а§Еа§Ва§Ча•На§∞а•За§Ьа§Ља•А) (а§Еа§Ва§Ча•На§∞а•За§Ьа§Ља•А); а§Ѓа•За§∞а•Ла§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Ђа§Ља•На§Є), а§Ьа•Л а§Ха§њ а§ђа§Ч-а§Єа•На§Єа•На§Єа•На§Єа•На§Єа•На§Єа•НвАМ (а§Еа§Ва§Ча•На§∞а•За§Ьа§Ља•А), а§ђа§Ч-а§Єа•НвАМ, а§ђа§Ч-а§Єа•НвАМ, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•Аа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Ђа§Ља•Йа§Єа•НвАМ (а§Еа§Ва§Ча•На§∞а•За§Ьа§Ља•А), а§ђа§Ч-а§Єа•НвАМ, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•За§∞а•Ла§Єа§ња§Є (а§Еа§Ва§Ча•На§∞а•За§Ьа§Ља•А), а§Ѓа•За§∞а•Ла§Єа§ња§Є (а§Еа§Ва§Ча•На§∞а•За§Ьа§Ља•А), а§ђа§Ч-а§Єа•НвАМ, а§ђа§Ча•Ба§≤а•Ла§Є), а§Ѓа•За§∞а•Ла§Єа§ња§Є (а§Еа§Ва§Ча•На§∞а•За§Ьа§Ља•А).",
  "What are lysosomes, and what happens when lysosomal function is impaired?": "а§Ха•На§ѓа§Њ а§За§Єа§Ха§Њ а§Ѓа§§а§≤а§ђ а§ѓа§є а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§Ьа§ђ а§ґа§∞а•Аа§∞ а§Ѓа•За§В а§∞а•Ла§Ч а§єа•Ла§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§§а•Л а§За§Єа§Ха§Њ а§Еа§Ва§Ьа§Ња§Ѓ а§ђа§єа•Ба§§ а§ђа•Ба§∞а§Њ а§єа•Ла§§а§Њ а§єа•И?",
  "Lysosomes are membrane-bound organelles containing ~50 types of hydrolytic (digestive) enzymes that function at acidic pH вАФ they break down worn-out organelles (autophagy), engulfed pathogens (phagocytosis), and macromolecules вАФ when lysosomal enzymes are deficient, undigested material accumulates, causing lysosomal storage diseases": "Loundys soundys, а§Ьа§ња§Єа§Ѓа•За§В 50 а§§а§∞а§є а§Ха•З а§Еа§£а•Ба§Уа§В (а§°а§ња§Єа•На§Ха§ња§Х а§Ѓа•За§В) а§єа•Ла§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В, а§µа•З websssse-sssseciols а§Ха•Л а§§а•Ла§°а§Љ а§¶а§ња§ѓа§Њ а§єа•И, а§Фа§∞ logsss (cropsssssss) вАФ а§Ьа§ђ а§™а•На§∞а§Ња§Ха•Га§§а§ња§Х а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Єа•З а§Еа§≠а§ња§Х а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Єа•З а§Еа§≠а•На§ѓ а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Єа•З, а§≠а•Ма§§а§ња§Х а§™а§¶а§Ња§∞а•На§• а§За§Ха§Яа•На§†а§Њ а§Ха§∞ а§∞а§єа•З а§єа•Иа§В, а§™а§¶а§Ња§∞а•На§• а§™а§¶а§Ња§∞а•На§• а§Ьа§Ѓа§Њ а§Ха§∞ а§∞а§єа•З а§єа•Иа§В, а§™а§¶а§Ња§∞а•На§• а§Ьа§Ѓа§Њ а§Ха§∞а§®а•З а§Ха•З а§≤а§ња§Па•§",
  "Lysosomes are organelles that produce new proteins by translating mRNA вАФ when impaired, the cell simply produces proteins more slowly but suffers no other consequences, involving the coordinated activity of organelles, enzymes, and signaling pathways that regulate cellular function and reproduction": "а§Ха•Ба§Ы а§Ра§Єа•З а§≠а•А а§єа•Ла§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В, а§Ьа•Л а§ґа§∞а•Аа§∞ а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Яа•Аа§® а§Ха§Њ а§За§Єа•На§§а•За§Ѓа§Ња§≤ а§Ха§∞а§Ха•З а§®а§ѓа•А а§™а•На§∞а•Ла§Яа•Аа§® а§§а•Иа§ѓа§Ња§∞ а§Ха§∞а§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В а•§",
  "Lysosomes are the site of DNA replication in the cell вАФ when impaired, cells cannot divide but all other cellular functions continue normally, as governed by the molecular machinery of gene expression, protein synthesis, and intracellular transport within living cells overall": "а§Ьа§ђ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ѓа•За§В а§°а•А. а§Па§®. а§П.",
  "Lysosomes are structural scaffolds that support the cell membrane from the inside вАФ when impaired, cells simply become floppier but continue to function normally without any disease, which has been well-documented through controlled experimental studies and long-term ecological monitoring programs across many regions": "Looooss а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§Еа§Ва§¶а§∞ а§Єа•З а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ха•А а§Эа§ња§≤а•На§≤а•А а§Ха§Њ а§Єа§Ѓа§∞а•На§•а§® а§Ха§∞а§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В а§Ьа•Л а§ґа§∞а•Аа§∞ а§Ха•З а§Еа§Ва§¶а§∞ а§Ха•З а§Еа§Ва§¶а§∞ а§Єа•З а§Еа§Ва§¶а§∞ а§Ха•А а§Уа§∞ а§єа•И вАФ а§Ьа§ђ а§Ыа•За§¶, а§Ьа§ђ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ха•Л а§Ха•За§µа§≤ а§Єа§єа§Ь а§ђа§® а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§≤а•За§Ха§ња§® а§Єа§Ња§Ѓа§Ња§®а•На§ѓ а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Єа•З а§Ха§ња§Єа•А а§≠а•А а§ђа•Аа§Ѓа§Ња§∞а•А а§Ха•З а§ђа§ња§®а§Њ, а§Ьа•Л а§ђа§єа•Ба§§ а§Єа§Ња§∞а•З а§Ха•На§Ја•За§§а•На§∞а•Ла§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§®а§ња§ѓа§Ва§§а•На§∞а§ња§§ а§Ха§ња§ѓа•З а§Ча§П а§™а§∞а•Аа§Ха•На§Ја§£а•Ла§В а§Фа§∞ а§≤а§Ва§ђа•З а§Єа§Ѓа§ѓ а§§а§Х а§®а§ња§Ја•На§Ха•На§∞а§ња§ѓ а§Ха§Ња§∞а•На§ѓа§Ха•На§∞а§Ѓа•Ла§В а§Ха•Л а§®а§ња§ѓа§Ва§§а•На§∞а§ња§§ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ча§ѓа§Њ а§єа•И",
  "Lysosomes вАФ cellular recycling center: (1) Discovery: Christian de Duve (Nobel Prize 1974) вАФ discovered lysosomes using cell fractionation and centrifugation. (2) Structure: single membrane. Interior maintained at pH 4.5-5.0 by vacuolar HвБЇ-ATPase (proton pumps). ~50+ types of acid hydrolases (active only at acidic pH вАФ safety mechanism: if lysosome ruptures, enzymes are inactive at cytoplasmic pH ~7.2). (3) Functions: autophagy (recycling worn-out organelles вАФ mitochondria every ~10 days вЖТ mitophagy), phagocytosis (immune cells digest engulfed pathogens: phagosome + lysosome вЖТ phagolysosome), endocytosis (break down materials brought into cell), apoptosis (programmed cell death when lysosomal membrane permeabilizes вЖТ cathepsins released). (4) Lysosomal storage diseases (~50 known): genetic deficiency of specific lysosomal enzyme вЖТ substrate accumulates. Tay-Sachs: hexosaminidase A deficiency вЖТ GM2 ganglioside accumulates in neurons вЖТ neurodegeneration, death by age 4-5 (carrier frequency 1/30 in Ashkenazi Jewish population). Gaucher disease: glucocerebrosidase deficiency вЖТ glucocerebroside accumulates in macrophages вЖТ enlarged spleen/liver (most common lysosomal storage disease; treatable with enzyme replacement therapy вАФ imiglucerase). Pompe disease: acid maltase deficiency вЖТ glycogen accumulates вЖТ muscle weakness. (5) Autophagy research: Yoshinori Ohsumi, Nobel Prize 2016 вАФ elucidated mechanisms of autophagy in yeast.": "а§За§Є а§§а§∞а§є а§Ха•З а§∞а•Ла§Ча•Ла§В а§Ха•З а§ђа§Ња§∞а•З а§Ѓа•За§В а§Ца•Ла§Ь а§Ха•А а§Ча§И а§Ьа§Ња§®а§Ха§Ња§∞а•А (а§Еа§Ва§Ча•На§∞а•За§Ьа§Ља•А) а§Ѓа•За§В, а§°а•Й. а§Яа•А. а§ђа•А.",
  "What are the three main components of the cytoskeleton, and what functions does each perform?": "а§Єа•А. а§Ха•З а§§а•Аа§® а§Ѓа•Ба§Ца•На§ѓ а§Еа§µа§ѓа§µ а§Ха•На§ѓа§Њ а§єа•Иа§В, а§Фа§∞ а§єа§∞ а§µа•На§ѓа§Ха•НвАНа§§а§њ а§Ха•Ма§® - а§Єа•З а§Ха§Ња§∞а•На§ѓ а§Ха§∞а§§а§Њ а§єа•И?",
  "The cytoskeleton is made of carbohydrate chains, lipid tubules, and nucleic acid filaments вАФ it functions only during cell division and disassembles between divisions": "",
