  "Cell theory вАФ three tenets and historical context: (1) First tenet: all living organisms are composed of one or more cells (unicellular: bacteria, protists, some fungi; multicellular: plants, animals, most fungi). Viruses are not cells and are debated as 'living.' (2) Second tenet: the cell is the fundamental unit of structure (smallest unit that displays all characteristics of life) and function in all living organisms. (3) Third tenet: all cells arise from pre-existing cells by division вАФ Virchow's 'omnis cellula e cellula' (1855) definitively refuted spontaneous generation for cells. (4) Modern additions: cells contain hereditary information (DNA/RNA) that is passed during division; all cells have the same basic chemical composition (water, organic molecules, ions); energy flow (metabolism) occurs within cells. (5) Exceptions/special cases: striated muscle fibers (syncytia вАФ multinucleated), red blood cells (anucleate in mammals вАФ lose nucleus during maturation), viruses (not cells, but can reproduce using host cells). (6) Importance: unifying principle that connects all of biology вАФ from molecular biology to ecology.": "а§Ха§Ха•На§Ј а§Єа§ња§¶а•На§Іа§Ња§Ва§§ вАФ а§§а•Аа§® а§Ча•Ба§£ а§Фа§∞ а§Ра§§а§ња§єа§Ња§Єа§ња§Х а§Єа§Ва§¶а§∞а•На§≠: (а•І) а§Єа§≠а•А а§Ьа•Аа§µа§ња§§ а§™а•На§∞а§Ња§£а•А а§Па§Х а§ѓа§Њ а§Йа§Єа§Єа•З а§Еа§Іа§ња§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Єа•З а§ђа§®а•З а§єа•Ла§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В (а§Ьа•Ла§≤а§Ња§И, а§Ьа•Аа§µ - а§µа§ња§Ьа•На§Юа§Ња§®, а§Ха•Ба§Ы а§Ра§Єа•А а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Єа•З а§ђа§®а§Њ а§єа•Ла§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ьа•Л а§ђа§єа•Ба§§ а§єа•А а§Ѓа§Ьа§Ља•За§¶а§Ња§∞ а§єа•Ла§§а•А а§єа•И: а§™а•Ма§Іа•Ла§В, а§Ьа§Ња§®а§µа§∞а•Ла§В, а§Єа§ђа§Єа•З а§Ѓа§Ьа§Ља•За§¶а§Ња§∞ а§єа•Ла§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В а•§ (а•®)",
