  "The tagging problem only affects bacteria inside the child's gut вАФ I-cell disease is actually caused by antibiotic-resistant bacteria that cannot be tagged for immune destruction, involving comprehensive analysis of genomic markers and heritable phenotypic variation within and between natural populations": "а§Ча§∞а•На§≠ а§Ча§ња§∞а§®а•З а§Ха•А а§Єа§Ѓа§Єа•На§ѓа§Њ а§Ха•За§µа§≤ а§ђа§Ъа•На§Ъа•З а§Ха•З а§™а•За§Я а§Ха•З а§Еа§Ва§¶а§∞ а§Ьа•Аа§µа§Ња§£а•Ба•Ла§В а§Ха•Л а§™а•На§∞а§≠а§Ња§µа§ња§§ а§Ха§∞а§§а•А а§єа•И - а§Ѓа•Иа§В scrasi-scipsienssiensssssiripstienss а§Ха•З а§Ѓа§Ња§Іа•На§ѓа§Ѓ а§Єа•З а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§µа§ња§®а§Ња§ґ а§Ха•З а§≤а§ња§П а§Яа•Иа§Ч а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Њ а§Єа§Ха§§а§Њ а§єа•И, а§Фа§∞ а§Йа§Єа§Ха•З а§µа•На§ѓа§Ња§™а§Х а§µа§ња§ґа•На§≤а•За§Ја§£ а§Фа§∞ а§™а•На§∞а§Ња§Ха•Га§§а§ња§Х а§Ьа§®а§Єа§Ва§Ца•На§ѓа§Њ а§Ха•З а§≠а•Аа§§а§∞ а§Фа§∞ а§Єа•На§µа§Ња§≠а§Ња§µа§ња§Х а§™а§∞а§ња§µа§∞а•На§§а§®а•Ла§В а§Ха•З а§ђа•Аа§Ъ а§Єа•На§µа§Ња§≠а§Ња§µа§ња§Х а§™а§∞а§ња§µа§∞а•На§§а§®а•Ла§В а§Ха•З а§ђа•Аа§Ъ а§Ѓа•За§В",
  "I-cell disease вАФ Golgi sorting failure: (1) Normal pathway: lysosomal enzymes are synthesized in RER вЖТ transported to Golgi вЖТ in cis-Golgi, GlcNAc phosphotransferase recognizes a signal patch on lysosomal enzyme вЖТ adds GlcNAc-phosphate to mannose residues вЖТ phosphodiesterase removes GlcNAc вЖТ exposed mannose-6-phosphate (M6P). In trans-Golgi network: M6P receptors bind M6P-tagged enzymes вЖТ clathrin-coated vesicles вЖТ late endosomes вЖТ lysosomes. Acidic pH causes enzyme release from M6P receptor вЖТ receptor recycled. (2) I-cell disease: GlcNAc phosphotransferase deficiency (GNPTAB gene mutations) вЖТ lysosomal enzymes lack M6P tag вЖТ not recognized by M6P receptors вЖТ follow default constitutive secretory pathway вЖТ secreted outside cell. Diagnostic: elevated lysosomal enzyme levels in blood/serum (because they're being secreted); deficient enzyme activity inside cells (because lysosomes are empty). (3) Consequences: lysosomes cannot degrade macromolecules вЖТ accumulation of undigested substrates вЖТ dense inclusion bodies in cells (visible under phase-contrast microscopy вЖТ 'inclusion cell' disease). Affects virtually all cell types. (4) Clinical: coarse facial features, skeletal dysplasia (dysostosis multiplex), severe psychomotor retardation, corneal clouding, gingival hyperplasia, hepatosplenomegaly. Usually fatal by age 5-8. (5) Demonstrates: the critical importance of protein sorting in the Golgi вАФ even though cells produce the needed enzymes, they're useless if delivered to the wrong destination.": "Iscrapsssocssssocsssochssssssssocherssssssssssssss. sowsochersssssssssssssss. swowocherssssssss. swocherowss. sowsowss. sows. sows. s. s. sowowowowsows. s. sows. sowows. sowowss. sowssss. sowows. lowows. s. lows. lows. low. lows. low. lopowowowowowows. s. s. lows. s. lows. lows. low. low. los. lomow. lomows. lopows. lows. s. s. s. low. s. s. s. low. s. low. low. s. s. low. s. low. low. lomow.",
  "A microbiologist isolates a mysterious single-celled organism from a deep-sea hydrothermal vent. Initial examination shows it is 0.8 ќЉm in diameter, has no visible nucleus, and can survive at 110¬∞C. However, further analysis reveals that its membrane contains ether-linked lipids and it has histone-like proteins bound to its circular DNA. How would you classify this organism, and why doesn't it fit neatly into the 'prokaryote' category as traditionally understood?": "а§Па§Х а§Єа•Ва§Ха•На§Ја•На§Ѓ а§Ьа•Аа§µ а§Ха•Л а§Еа§≤а§Ч а§Ха§∞а§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Па§Х а§∞а§єа§Єа•На§ѓ а§Єа•З а§Па§Х а§Ча§єа§∞а•А а§Єа•Аа§≤ scramomed. а§Жа§∞а§Ва§≠а§ња§Х а§Ьа§Ња§Ба§Ъ а§ѓа§є а§µа•На§ѓа§Ња§Є а§Ѓа•За§В а§єа•И, а§Ха•Ла§И а§¶а•Га§ґа•НвАНа§ѓ а§Ха•За§Ва§¶а•На§∞ а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§єа•И, а§Фа§∞ 110C а§Ѓа•За§В а§Ьа•Аа§µа§ња§§ а§∞а§є а§Єа§Ха§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В. а§єа§Ња§≤а§Ња§Ва§Ха§њ, а§Еа§Іа§ња§Х а§µа§ња§ґа•На§≤а•За§Ја§£ а§™а•На§∞а§Ха§Я а§Ха§∞а§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§За§Єа§Ха•З а§Ъа§∞а§ња§§а•На§∞ а§Ѓа•За§В elids а§ґа§Ња§Ѓа§ња§≤ а§єа•И а§Фа§∞ а§ѓа§є а§Еа§™а§®а•А а§Па§®-а§∞а•Ва§Я-а§За§®а•На§Є а§Фа§∞ а§За§Єа•З а§Па§Х а§§а§∞а§є а§Єа•З а§ђа§Ња§Іа•На§ѓ а§Ха§∞а§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§Ха•Иа§Єа•З а§Жа§™ а§ѓа§є а§µа§∞а•На§Ч а§Ѓа•За§В а§Ђа§ња§Я а§Ха§∞а§®а•З а§Ха•З а§≤а§ња§П а§Єа§Ха•На§Ја§Ѓ а§єа•И, а§Фа§∞ а§ѓа§є а§µа§∞а•На§Ч а§Ѓа•За§В а§Ђа§ња§Я а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§єа•И?",
  "This organism is likely an archaeon вАФ archaea are prokaryotic in structure but share several molecular features with eukaryotes, including histone-like proteins, some eukaryotic-type transcription/translation machinery, and ether-linked lipids вАФ this is why the three-domain system (Woese, 1990) separates Bacteria and Archaea, recognizing that 'prokaryote' lumps together two fundamentally different groups": "",
  "It must be a eukaryote because it has histone-like proteins вАФ all organisms with any histone proteins have a nucleus, and the microscopist must have missed it, as determined through molecular analysis of DNA sequence variation and allele frequency distributions across sampled populations": "",
  "It is a very small plant cell that has lost its chloroplasts due to the absence of light at hydrothermal vents вАФ the histone proteins confirm it is a plant, measured by comparing heritable allelic variation among individuals within geographically defined breeding populations over generations": "",
  "It must be a virus since it is smaller than 1 ќЉm and lacks a nucleus вАФ viruses commonly have histone-like proteins and ether-linked lipids, involving comprehensive analysis of genomic markers and heritable phenotypic variation within and between natural populations": "",
  "Archaea and the three domains: (1) Carl Woese (1977) used 16S rRNA sequencing to discover that 'prokaryotes' are actually two fundamentally different groups: Bacteria and Archaea. Led to the three-domain system (1990): Bacteria, Archaea, Eukarya. (2) Archaea вАФ prokaryotic structure: no nuclear membrane, no membrane-bound organelles, small size (0.1-15 ќЉm), circular chromosome(s), binary fission. BUT molecular features are a mosaic of bacterial AND eukaryotic traits. (3) Archaeal features shared with eukaryotes (not bacteria): histone-like proteins (archaeal histones wrap DNA similarly to eukaryotic nucleosomes), RNA polymerase similar to eukaryotic RNA Pol II (multi-subunit), TATA-binding protein (TBP) in transcription initiation, translation initiation with methionine (not formyl-methionine as in bacteria), some introns in tRNA genes. (4) Unique archaeal features: ether-linked lipids (isoprenoid chains linked to glycerol via ether bonds, vs. ester bonds in bacteria/eukaryotes вЖТ more heat-stable), some form lipid monolayers (tetraether lipids spanning entire membrane вАФ extremely stable at high temperatures), unique cell wall composition (no peptidoglycan вАФ pseudopeptidoglycan, S-layer, or none). (5) Extremophile archaea: thermophiles (Pyrolobus fumarii вАФ up to 113¬∞C), halophiles (Halobacterium вАФ 5M NaCl), acidophiles (Sulfolobus вАФ pH 1-2), methanogens (Methanobacterium вАФ strict anaerobes, produce CHвВД). But archaea also live in 'normal' environments вАФ abundant in ocean water, soil, human gut. (6) Phylogenetic implication: Archaea + Eukaryota form a clade to the exclusion of Bacteria. Eukaryotes likely evolved from an archaeal ancestor (Asgard archaea вАФ Lokiarchaeota discovered 2015 вАФ closest known archaeal relatives of eukaryotes).": "",
  "A patient with primary ciliary dyskinesia (PCD, also called Kartagener syndrome when accompanied by situs inversus) suffers from chronic respiratory infections, infertility, and has a 50% chance of having mirror-reversed organ placement. His physician explains that all these symptoms result from defective cilia. How can one structural defect вАФ in a cytoskeletal component вАФ cause such diverse symptoms across different organ systems?": "а§За§Єа§Ха•З а§°а•Йа§Ха•На§Яа§∞ а§ђа§§а§Ња§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В а§Ха§њ а§За§® а§Єа§≠а•А а§≤а§Ха•На§Ја§£а•Ла§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§ђа•Аа§Ѓа§Ња§∞а•А а§Ха•З а§≤а§Ха•На§Ја§£а•Ла§В а§Єа•З а§Ха•Иа§Єа•З а§Еа§≤а§Ч а§єа•Л а§Єа§Ха§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В а•§",
  "PCD is caused by overactive lysosomes digesting the respiratory epithelium вАФ the cilia are normal but the cells beneath them are destroyed, a concept that has been extensively studied and documented in ecological and evolutionary research across diverse biological systems": "а§ґа•НвАНа§µа•За§§ а§∞а§Ха•НвАНа§§а§™а§ња§≤ а§Ха•Л а§Ыа•Ва§®а•З а§Ха•З а§Ха§Ња§∞а§£, а§Па§°а§Єа•НвАМ а§Єа§Ња§Ѓа§Ња§®а•На§ѓ а§єа•И а§≤а•За§Ха§ња§® а§Йа§Єа§Ха•З а§®а•Аа§Ъа•З а§Ха•А а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ха•Л а§®а§Ја•На§Я а§Ха§∞ а§¶а§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И, а§Па§Х а§Іа§Ња§∞а§£а§Њ а§Ьа•Л а§µа•На§ѓа§Ња§™а§Х а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Єа•З а§Ъа§ња§Ха§ња§§а•На§Єа§Њ а§Фа§∞ а§µа•Иа§Ьа•На§Юа§Ња§®а§ња§Х а§Еа§®а•Ба§Єа§Ва§Іа§Ња§®а•Ла§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§µа§ња§ґа•НвАНа§≤а•За§Ја§£ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ча§ѓа§Њ а§єа•И",
  "PCD only affects the lungs вАФ the infertility and organ reversal are caused by separate, unrelated genetic mutations that happen to occur together frequently, measured by comparing heritable allelic variation among individuals within geographically defined breeding populations over generations": "PCD а§Єа§ња§∞а•На§Ђа§Љ а§Ђа•За§Ђа§°а§Ља•Ла§В а§Ха•Л а§™а•На§∞а§≠а§Ња§µа§ња§§ а§Ха§∞а§§а§Њ а§єа•И вАФ а§Еа§™а•На§∞а§ѓа•Ла§Ча•Аа§ѓа§§а§Њ а§Фа§∞ а§¶а•Ва§Єа§∞а•З а§ђа§¶а§≤а§Ња§µ а§Еа§≤а§Ч - а§Еа§≤а§Ч а§єа•Ла§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В, а§Ьа•Л а§Еа§Ха§Єа§∞ а§Па§Х а§Єа§Ња§• а§єа•Ла§®а•З а§Ха•З а§Ха§Ња§∞а§£ а§єа•Ла§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В а•§",
  "PCD is caused by excess actin microfilaments clogging the airways вАФ the organ reversal happens because microfilaments push organs to the wrong side during development, which has been well-documented through controlled experimental studies and long-term ecological monitoring programs across many regions": "PDD а§Ха•З а§Ха§Ња§∞а§£ а§ђа§єа•Ба§§ а§Єа§Ња§∞а•З а§Ха•На§Ја•За§§а•На§∞а•Ла§В а§Ха•З а§™а§Ња§∞, а§µа§Ња§ѓа•Б а§Ха•Л а§™а•На§∞а§µа§Ња§єа§ња§§ а§Ха§∞а§®а•З а§Ха•З а§Ха§Ња§∞а§£ а§єа•Ла§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ха•На§ѓа•Ла§Ва§Ха§њ а§µа§Ња§ѓа•Ба§Ѓа§Ва§°а§≤ а§Ха•Л а§Йа§≤а§Яа§Њ а§єа•Ла§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§За§Єа§≤а§ња§П а§Ха§њ а§Ѓа§Ња§За§Ха•На§∞а•Ла§Єа•На§Ха•Ла§™ а§Єа•З, а§µа§ња§Ха§Ња§Є а§Ха•З а§¶а•Ма§∞а§Ња§® а§Ча§≤а§§ а§™а§Ха•На§Ј а§Ѓа•За§В, а§Ьа•Л а§Ха§њ а§ђа§єа•Ба§§ а§Єа§Ња§∞а•З а§Ха•На§Ја•За§§а•На§∞а•Ла§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§®а§ња§ѓа§Ва§§а•На§∞а§ња§§ а§Ха§ња§ѓа•З а§Ча§П а§Еа§Іа•На§ѓа§ѓа§®а•Ла§В а§Фа§∞ а§≤а§Ва§ђа•З а§Єа§Ѓа§ѓ а§§а§Х а§Ьа§Яа§ња§≤ а§Ьа§Ња§Ба§Ъ а§Ха§Ња§∞а•На§ѓа§Ха•На§∞а§Ѓа•Ла§В а§Ха•З а§Ѓа§Ња§Іа•На§ѓа§Ѓ а§Єа•З а§Еа§Ъа•На§Ыа•А а§§а§∞а§є а§Єа•З а§Ъа§≤а§Њ а§Ча§ѓа§Њ а§єа•И",
  "PCD is caused by mutations in dynein motor proteins of the 9+2 microtubule axoneme in motile cilia вАФ defective respiratory cilia cannot clear mucus from airways, defective flagella on sperm cannot propel them (вЖТ male infertility), defective cilia in fallopian tubes cannot move the egg (вЖТ female subfertility), and defective nodal cilia in the embryo cannot generate the left-right fluid flow that determines organ asymmetry": "PCD а§Ха§Њ а§Ха§Ња§∞а§£ а§єа•И 9nytotocayyyyoliols а§Ѓа•За§В а§Йа§§а•На§™а§∞а§ња§µа§∞а•На§§а§® а§Ха•З а§Ха§Ња§∞а§£ а§єа•Ла§§а§Њ а§єа•И scenty symoliol а§Ѓа•За§В а§Па§Х mymymomy styyyyyyyy sta s а§Єа•З а§Єа•На§™а§Ја•На§Я а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§Ха§∞ а§Єа§Ха§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В, а§Ча§∞а•На§≠ а§Ѓа•За§В а§Еа§≠а§£а§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§Ха§Ѓа•А а§™а•Иа§¶а§Њ а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§Ха§∞ а§Єа§Ха§§а•А а§єа•И, а§Фа§∞ а§® а§єа•А а§Ча§∞а•На§≠ а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а•На§∞а§µа•За§ґ а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§Ха§∞ а§Єа§Ха§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§Еа§≠а§£а§£а•НвАНа§®а§£а•НвАНа§®а§£а§£а•НвАНа§§ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а•На§∞а§µа•За§ґ а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§Ха§∞ а§Єа§Ха§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В, а§Фа§∞ а§® а§єа•А а§Ча§∞а•На§≠ а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а•На§∞а§µа•За§ґ а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§Ха§∞ а§Єа§Ха§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В, а§Фа§∞ а§® а§єа•А а§Ча§∞а•На§≠ а§Ѓа•За§В а§™а•На§∞а§µа•За§ґ а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§Ха§∞ а§Єа§Ха§§а•З а§єа•Иа§В, а§ѓа§є а§®а§ња§∞а•На§Іа§Ња§∞а§ња§§ а§Ха§∞а§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§Ха•Ла§И а§≠а•А а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§єа•Ла§§а§Њ а§єа•И",
  "Primary ciliary dyskinesia вАФ one cytoskeletal defect, many organ systems: (1) Motile cilia structure: 9+2 axoneme (9 outer doublet microtubules + 2 central singlets). Outer and inner dynein arms (molecular motors) on outer doublets generate sliding force вЖТ bending. Nexin links and radial spokes coordinate bending вЖТ rhythmic beating pattern (~10-20 Hz). (2) PCD genetics: autosomal recessive. ~50 genes known. Most common: DNAI1, DNAH5 (outer dynein arm components). ~1/15,000-20,000 births. (3) Respiratory consequences: airway cilia (in trachea, bronchi вАФ mucociliary escalator) beat in coordinated waves to move mucus + trapped particles upward toward pharynx вЖТ clearance. Defective cilia вЖТ mucus stagnation вЖТ bacterial colonization вЖТ chronic sinusitis, bronchitis, bronchiectasis (permanent airway dilation), otitis media. (4) Fertility: sperm flagellum has 9+2 axoneme (same dynein motors) вЖТ immotile sperm вЖТ male infertility. Fallopian tube cilia move ovum вЖТ female subfertility. (5) Situs inversus (Kartagener syndrome, ~50% of PCD): during embryonic development (day 7-8), nodal cilia at the embryonic node rotate clockwise вЖТ create leftward fluid flow вЖТ asymmetric gene expression (Nodal, Lefty, Pitx2) вЖТ normal left-right organ placement (situs solitus). Immotile nodal cilia вЖТ no directional flow вЖТ organ placement is random (50:50 normal or mirror-image). Most situs inversus patients are clinically normal (mirror-image organs work fine) unless accompanied by cardiac defects (heterotaxy). (6) Demonstrates: the cytoskeleton isn't just structural вАФ microtubule-based motility is essential for mucus clearance, reproduction, and embryonic development.": "",
  "An evolutionary biologist compares the genomes of mitochondria and the free-living bacterium Rickettsia prowazekii (which causes epidemic typhus). She finds remarkable similarities: both have circular DNA, similar gene sequences, and both encode components of the electron transport chain. However, the mitochondrial genome is much smaller (~16,500 bp vs. ~1.1 million bp). What does this evidence tell us about the origin of mitochondria, and why has the mitochondrial genome shrunk?": "",
  "This evidence strongly supports the endosymbiotic theory: mitochondria descended from a free-living ќ±-proteobacterium that was engulfed by an ancestral eukaryotic cell ~1.5-2 billion years ago вАФ the mitochondrial genome shrank because most genes were transferred to the host cell's nuclear DNA over evolutionary time, leaving only 37 genes in human mtDNA вАФ the mitochondrion became dependent on the host for most proteins, which are now imported via the TOM/TIM translocation complexes": "",
  "The similarities are purely coincidental вАФ mitochondria and Rickettsia evolved independently, and circular DNA is found in all organisms, making it a meaningless comparison, as determined through molecular analysis of DNA sequence variation and allele frequency distributions across sampled populations": "",
  "Mitochondria are actually modified peroxisomes that acquired DNA from Rickettsia through horizontal gene transfer in the modern era вАФ they have no ancient evolutionary origin, measured by comparing heritable allelic variation among individuals within geographically defined breeding populations over generations": "",
  "The smaller mitochondrial genome proves that mitochondria are degenerate viruses that lost most of their genes after infecting eukaryotic cells вАФ they are parasites, not symbionts, involving comprehensive analysis of genomic markers and heritable phenotypic variation within and between natural populations": "",
  "Endosymbiotic theory and mitochondrial genome evolution: (1) Endosymbiotic theory (Lynn Margulis, 1967; originally proposed by Konstantin Mereschkowski, 1905, and Ivan Wallin, 1927): an ancestral anaerobic eukaryote engulfed an aerobic ќ±-proteobacterium вЖТ mutualistic endosymbiosis (host provided nutrients, endosymbiont provided efficient aerobic ATP production). Over ~1.5-2 billion years вЖТ obligate symbiosis вЖТ mitochondrion. (2) Evidence: double membrane (inner = original bacterial membrane, outer = host's phagosomal membrane); circular DNA (like bacteria); 70S ribosomes (like bacteria, not eukaryotic 80S); binary fission-like division (independent of cell cycle); cardiolipin in inner membrane (bacterial membrane lipid); phylogenetics: mitochondrial rRNA sequences cluster within ќ±-proteobacteria, closest to Rickettsiales. (3) Genome reduction: human mtDNA = 16,569 bp (37 genes: 13 proteins for ETC/ATP synthase + 22 tRNAs + 2 rRNAs). Rickettsia prowazekii = ~1.1 Mb. ќ±-proteobacterial ancestor likely had ~3,000-4,000 genes. (4) Endosymbiotic gene transfer (EGT): over evolutionary time, most mitochondrial genes were transferred to the nuclear genome. ~1,500 nuclear-encoded proteins are now imported into mitochondria via TOM (translocase of outer membrane) and TIM (translocase of inner membrane) complexes, using N-terminal targeting sequences (mitochondrial targeting peptides). (5) Why retain any genes? Some highly hydrophobic inner membrane proteins may be difficult to import from cytoplasm. Co-location for redox regulation (CoRR) hypothesis: keeping genes in mitochondria allows local regulation of gene expression in response to respiratory chain status.": "",
  "A research team generates the first complete synthetic bacterial genome (Craig Venter's team, 2010 вАФ Mycoplasma mycoides JCVI-syn1.0) and transplants it into a different species of Mycoplasma whose own genome has been removed. The cell with the synthetic genome boots up, begins transcribing genes, and divides. Some commentators call this 'creating life.' Using your knowledge of cell theory and cell structure, evaluate this claim.": "",
  "The experiment failed because the transplanted genome was immediately destroyed by the host cell's immune system вАФ Mycoplasma cells have restriction enzymes that digest any foreign DNA": "",
  "This clearly created life from scratch вАФ since DNA is the only component needed for a cell, inserting synthetic DNA into an empty lipid vesicle would have worked equally well": "",
  "This experiment disproved cell theory by showing that cells can arise from non-living synthetic chemicals вАФ it proved that spontaneous generation is possible under laboratory conditions": "а§За§Є а§™а•На§∞а§ѓа•Ла§Ч а§®а•За§≤ а§Єа§ња§¶а•На§Іа§Ња§Ва§§ а§Ха•Л а§Єа§Ња§ђа§ња§§ а§Ха§∞а§®а•З а§Ха•З а§¶а•На§µа§Ња§∞а§Њ а§ѓа§є а§Єа§Ња§ђа§ња§§ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ха§њ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ча•Иа§∞ а§Ьа•Аа§µа§ња§§ а§∞а§Єа§Ња§ѓа§®а•Ла§В а§Єа•З а§Йа§§а•На§™а§®а•НвАНа§® а§єа•Л а§Єа§Ха§§а§Њ а§єа•И вАФ а§ѓа§є а§Єа§Ња§ђа§ња§§ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ха§њ а§Єа•На§µа§Ња§≠а§Ња§µа§ња§Х а§™а•Аа§Ґа§Ља•А а§™а•На§∞а§ѓа•Ла§Ча§ґа§Ња§≤а§Њ а§™а§∞а§ња§Єа•На§•а§ња§§а§ња§ѓа•Ла§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§Єа§Ва§≠а§µ а§єа•И",
  "This did NOT create life from non-living matter вАФ the synthetic genome was inserted into an existing cell that already had all the necessary cellular machinery (ribosomes, enzymes, membranes, metabolites, ATP, tRNAs) вАФ cell theory states all cells come from pre-existing cells, and this experiment still required a pre-existing cell as the 'operating system' to read and execute the new genomic 'software' вАФ it demonstrated that DNA is the informational blueprint, but a cell is far more than its genome": "а§ѓа§є а§Ха§ња§Єа•А а§≠а•А а§Ьа•Аа§µа§ња§§ а§™а§¶а§Ња§∞а•На§• а§Єа•З а§Ьа•Аа§µа§® а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§ђа§®а§Ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ча§ѓа§Њ а§єа•И, а§ђа§≤а•На§Ха§њ а§ѓа§є а§Па§Х а§Ѓа•Ма§Ьа•Ва§¶а§Њ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ѓа•За§В а§ґа§Ња§Ѓа§ња§≤ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ча§ѓа§Њ а§•а§Њ а§Ьа•Л а§™а§єа§≤а•З а§Єа•З а§єа•А а§Єа§≠а•А а§Жа§µа§ґа•На§ѓа§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ, а§Ха§ња§≤а•НвАМа§Є, а§®а§≤а§ња§ѓа•Ла§В, а§®а§≤а§ња§ѓа•Ла§В, ATP, ATP, HINDNDNDINDIC а§Ха•З а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Ѓа•За§В а§Жа§§а§Њ а§єа•И, а§Фа§∞ а§За§Є а§™а•На§∞а§ѓа•Ла§Ч а§Ѓа•За§В а§Еа§≠а•А а§≠а•А а§Па§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ха•З а§™а•Ва§∞а•На§µ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Єа•З а§Жа§ѓа§Њ а§єа•И, а§Фа§∞ а§За§Є а§™а•На§∞а§ѓа•Ла§Ч а§Ха•А а§Ѓа§Ња§Ба§Ч а§Ха•А а§Ча§И а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§Па§Х а§®а§ѓа•А а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ха•З а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Ѓа•За§В а§ѓа§є а§Еа§ђ а§§а§Х а§™а•На§∞а§¶а§∞а•На§ґа§ња§§ а§Ха§∞а§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§ѓа§є а§Па§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§єа•И, а§≤а•За§Ха§ња§® а§ѓа§є а§Еа§ђ а§§а§Х а§™а•На§∞а§¶а§∞а•На§ґа§ња§§ а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§ѓа§є а§Па§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Єа•З а§Еа§Іа§ња§Х а§єа•И, а§≤а•За§Ха§ња§® а§ѓа§є а§Па§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§ѓа§є а§Па§Х а§Ьа§Яа§ња§≤ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Єа•З а§Еа§Іа§ња§Х а§Єа•З а§Еа§Іа§ња§Х а§єа•И, а§≤а•За§Ха§ња§® а§ѓа§є а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§ѓа§є а§Па§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Єа•З а§Еа§Іа§ња§Х а§Ьа§Ња§®а§Ха§Ња§∞а•А а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§ѓа§є а§єа•И, а§≤а•За§Ха§ња§® а§ѓа§є а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§ѓа§є а§Па§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ха•З а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Ѓа•За§В а§Єа•З а§Еа§Іа§ња§Х а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§ѓа§є а§Па§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§єа•И, а§≤а•За§Ха§ња§® а§ѓа§є а§Па§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ха•З а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Ѓа•За§В а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§ѓа§є а§Па§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ха•З а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Ѓа•За§В а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§єа•И, а§≤а•За§Ха§ња§® а§ѓа§є а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§ѓа§є а§Па§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§ѓа§є а§Па§Х а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§єа•И, а§Ьа•Ла§≤ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ха•З а§∞а•Ва§™ а§Ѓа•За§В а§єа•И",
  "Synthetic biology and cell theory: (1) Craig Venter's experiment (2010, Science): synthesized the complete 1.08 Mb genome of Mycoplasma mycoides from chemically synthesized oligonucleotides вЖТ assembled in yeast вЖТ transplanted into Mycoplasma capricolum recipient cell whose own genome had been removed. The 'rebooted' cell expressed the synthetic M. mycoides genome, produced M. mycoides proteins, and divided вЖТ established a self-replicating strain (JCVI-syn1.0). (2) What it demonstrated: DNA is the software that directs cellular behavior. Even a completely synthetic genome can direct a living cell. Genome transplantation effectively converts one species into another. (3) What it did NOT demonstrate: creation of life from scratch. The experiment absolutely required a pre-existing cell with intact: ribosomes (to translate the new genome), RNA polymerase (to transcribe it), ATP and metabolites (to power initial gene expression), the entire membrane system (to contain everything), tRNAs, amino acids, nucleotides, etc. (4) Cell theory analysis: tenet 3 ('all cells from pre-existing cells') was upheld вАФ the synthetic cell arose from a pre-existing cell. The genome was new, but the cell was not. A thought experiment: if you put the synthetic genome into a test tube with only water and salts вАФ nothing would happen. The cell is the minimal unit of life, not the genome alone. (5) Later work: JCVI-syn3.0 (2016) вАФ minimal genome of 473 genes (149 of unknown function!) вАФ the smallest genome that can sustain independent life. Still required a recipient cell. (6) Philosophical: the experiment blurs the line between natural and artificial but reinforces, rather than refutes, cell theory.": "TBIPERIPEE (а§Еа§Ва§Ча•На§∞а•За§Ьа§Ља•А) а§Ѓа•За§В а§Ьа•Аа§µ а§µа§ња§Ьа•На§Юа§Ња§® а§Фа§∞ а§Ьа•Аа§µ а§µа§ња§Ьа•На§Юа§Ња§® (а§Еа§Ва§Ча•На§∞а•За§Ьа§Ља•А) а§Ха§Њ а§™а§∞а•Аа§Ха•На§Ја§£ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ча§ѓа§Њ, а§Ьа§ња§Єа§Ѓа•За§В а§Ьа•Аа§µ а§µа§ња§Ьа•На§Юа§Ња§® а§Ха•З а§ђа§Ња§∞а•З а§Ѓа•За§В а§Ха•Ла§И а§≠а•А а§Ьа§Ња§®а§Ха§Ња§∞а•А а§®а§єа•Аа§В а§¶а•А а§Ча§И а§•а•А. (а•І)",
  "An immunologist explains to medical students how macrophages destroy bacteria using an elegant coordination of multiple organelles. A macrophage engulfs a Staphylococcus aureus bacterium. Trace the subsequent events, identifying each organelle involved and its role in the process.": "а§Ъа§ња§Ха§ња§§а•На§Єа§Њ а§µа§ња§Ьа•На§Юа§Ња§® а§Ха•З а§Па§Х а§µа§ња§ґа•За§Ја§Ьа•На§Ю а§®а•З а§Ха§єа§Њ а§Ха§њ а§Ха§И а§§а§∞а•Аа§Ха•Ла§В а§Єа•З а§∞а•Ла§Ча§Ња§£а•Ба§Уа§В а§Ха•А а§Еа§Ъа•На§Ыа•А а§§а§∞а§є а§Ьа§Ња§Ба§Ъ - а§™а§∞а§Ц а§Ха§∞а§®а•З а§Ха•З а§≤а§ња§П а§Ьа•Аа§µа§Ња§£а•Ба§Уа§В а§Ха•Л а§®а§Ја•На§Я а§Ха§∞а§®а§Њ а§Ха§ња§§а§®а§Њ а§Ьа§Ља§∞а•Ва§∞а•А а§єа•И а•§",
  "Smooth ER wraps around the bacterium and uses cytochrome P450 enzymes to oxidize it вАФ the Golgi then packages the oxidized remains into secretory vesicles that are expelled from the cell, involving the coordinated activity of organelles, enzymes, and signaling pathways that regulate cellular function and reproduction": "а§За§Є а§§а§∞а§є а§Ха•З а§™а•Иа§Ха•За§Ьа•Ла§В а§Ха•Л а§Йа§Є а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Єа•З а§®а§ња§Ха§Ња§≤ а§¶а§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ьа§ња§Єа§Ѓа•За§В а§®а§≤а§ња§ѓа•Ла§В, а§®а§≤а§ња§ѓа•Ла§В, а§®а§≤а§ња§ѓа•Ла§В, а§Фа§∞ а§Єа§Ва§Ха•За§§а•Ла§В а§Єа•З а§Ьа•Ба§°а§Ља•З а§Ха§Ња§Ѓа•Ла§В а§Ѓа•За§В а§ґа§Ња§Ѓа§ња§≤ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Њ а§Ха•Л а§®а§ња§ѓа§Ва§§а•На§∞а§ња§§ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Фа§∞ а§ѓа§є а§Єа§Ва§Ха•За§§ а§¶а•За§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Ха§њ а§Ха•Ла§ґа§ња§Ха§Ња§Уа§В а§Ха•Л а§™а•Ба§®а§Га§§а•На§∞а§ња§§ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И а§Фа§∞ а§Йа§Єа•З а§™а•Ба§®а§Га§§а•На§∞а§ња§§ а§Ха§ња§ѓа§Њ а§Ьа§Ња§§а§Њ а§єа•И",
  "The bacterium is immediately killed by the acidity of the cytoplasm (pH 2.0) вАФ no specific organelles are involved in the process, and the dead bacterium simply dissolves in the cytosol, as governed by the molecular machinery of gene expression, protein synthesis, and intracellular transport within living cells overall": "",
  "The macrophage extends pseudopodia to engulf the bacterium into a phagosome вЖТ the phagosome fuses with a lysosome to form a phagolysosome вЖТ lysosomal acid hydrolases digest the bacterium's proteins, lipids, carbohydrates, and nucleic acids вЖТ bacterial antigens are loaded onto MHC II molecules and presented on the cell surface вЖТ meanwhile, the Golgi packages and delivers new lysosomal enzymes and membrane components, mitochondria provide ATP for the energy-demanding process": "",
  "The bacterium enters the nucleus where DNA enzymes destroy it вАФ then the mitochondria digest the remains and excrete them through the cell membrane, involving the coordinated activity of organelles, enzymes, and signaling pathways that regulate cellular function and reproduction": "",
  "Phagocytosis вАФ organelle coordination in immune defense: (1) Recognition: macrophage receptors (Toll-like receptors/TLRs, Fc receptors, complement receptors, mannose receptors) bind PAMPs on bacterial surface or opsonins (antibodies, complement C3b). (2) Engulfment: actin polymerization (cytoskeleton) drives pseudopod extension вЖТ bacterium enclosed in phagosome (membrane-bound vacuole derived from plasma membrane). Energy: mitochondrial ATP powers actin dynamics and membrane remodeling. (3) Phagosome maturation: early phagosome (Rab5 GTPase, slight acidification) вЖТ late phagosome (Rab7, more acidification by V-ATPase) вЖТ phagolysosom–µ (fusion with lysosome). Fusion mediated by SNARE proteins, Rab GTPases. (4) Killing and digestion in phagolysosome: pH drops to ~4.5 (V-ATPase proton pumps). Acid hydrolases: cathepsins (proteases), lysozyme (cleaves peptidoglycan), DNase/RNase, lipases, glycosidases. Oxidative burst: NADPH oxidase вЖТ superoxide (OвВВвБївАҐ) вЖТ HвВВOвВВ вЖТ HOCl (myeloperoxidase) вАФ extremely bactericidal. iNOS вЖТ nitric oxide (NOвАҐ) вЖТ peroxynitrite (ONOOвБї). (5) Antigen presentation: bacterial protein fragments (peptides, 13-25 amino acids) loaded onto MHC class II molecules (assembled in ER, processed in Golgi) вЖТ transported to cell surface вЖТ presented to CD4вБЇ helper T cells вЖТ adaptive immune response initiation. ER and Golgi are essential for MHC synthesis and processing. (6) Waste disposal: indigested remnants expelled by exocytosis. (7) Summary of organelles: cell membrane (recognition/engulfment), cytoskeleton-actin (pseudopodia), lysosomes (digestion), mitochondria (ATP), ER (MHC/protein synthesis), Golgi (MHC processing/lysosomal enzyme delivery), endosomes (maturation pathway).": "",
  "A cell biologist discovers that a rare genetic mutation causes a patient's cells to completely lack peroxisomes (Zellweger spectrum disorder). The patient, an infant, has severe neurological dysfunction, liver disease, and abnormal facial features. Why would the absence of this single, seemingly minor organelle cause such devastating multi-organ failure?": "",
  "Peroxisomes are the organelles that produce all steroid hormones вАФ without them, the infant has no cortisol, estrogen, or testosterone, causing hormonal collapse, involving the coordinated activity of organelles, enzymes, and signaling pathways that regulate cellular function and reproduction": "",
  "Peroxisomes are needed only for detoxifying alcohol вАФ the infant's disease is actually caused by accidental alcohol exposure, not a genetic defect in peroxisomes, as governed by the molecular machinery of gene expression, protein synthesis, and intracellular transport within living cells overall": "",
  "Peroxisomes are the primary site of protein synthesis вАФ without them, cells cannot make any proteins and all organ systems fail simultaneously, through the action of specific biochemical pathways and regulatory mechanisms that maintain cellular homeostasis and normal growth": "",
  "Peroxisomes perform several essential metabolic functions that no other organelle can fully compensate for: (1) very-long-chain fatty acid (VLCFA) ќ≤-oxidation, (2) synthesis of plasmalogens, (3) bile acid synthesis, (4) hydrogen peroxide metabolism вАФ without peroxisomes, VLCFAs accumulate, plasmalogens are absent, bile synthesis fails (liver disease), and HвВВOвВВ accumulates (oxidative damage)": "",
  "Zellweger spectrum disorder вАФ peroxisomal absence: (1) Peroxisomes: single-membrane organelles (~0.1-1 ќЉm). Named for hydrogen peroxide (HвВВOвВВ) вАФ many peroxisomal oxidases produce HвВВOвВВ as byproduct вЖТ catalase breaks it down. ~50 enzymes. (2) Essential functions: VLCFA ќ≤-oxidation (fatty acids >C22 can ONLY be shortened in peroxisomes; after shortening to ~C8, acetyl-CoA units transferred to mitochondria for further oxidation). Plasmalogen synthesis (ether-phospholipids вАФ ~18% of brain phospholipids, critical component of myelin вАФ the insulating sheath around axons). ќ±-oxidation of branched-chain fatty acids (phytanic acid from dairy/meat). Bile acid synthesis (side-chain oxidation of cholesterol). Amino acid metabolism (D-amino acid oxidase, L-pipecolic acid oxidase). HвВВOвВВ detoxification (catalase вАФ one of the fastest enzymes known: ~40 million reactions/sec). (3) Zellweger syndrome (most severe of Zellweger spectrum): caused by mutations in PEX genes (peroxins вАФ ~16 known) needed for peroxisome biogenesis/assembly. Most common: PEX1 mutations (~60% of cases). Autosomal recessive. ~1/50,000 births. (4) Pathology: VLCFA accumulation (C26:0 elevated in blood вАФ diagnostic biomarker) вЖТ disrupts cell membranes, especially myelin вЖТ demyelination, neuronal migration defects вЖТ severe intellectual disability, seizures, hypotonia. Plasmalogen deficiency вЖТ defective myelin formation вЖТ compounds neurological damage. Bile acid synthetic intermediates accumulate вЖТ liver dysfunction (hepatomegaly, jaundice, fibrosis). Brain MRI: polymicrogyria (abnormal cortical gyral pattern), demyelination, germinolytic cysts. (5) Prognosis: most severe form (Zellweger syndrome) вЖТ death within 1st year. Milder forms (neonatal adrenoleukodystrophy, infantile Refsum disease): variable survival. No cure; treatment is supportive. (6) Demonstrates: 'minor' organelles perform unique, irreplaceable metabolic functions. The cell is an integrated system вАФ removing any component impacts the whole.": ""
